No, clearly not. The creature hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a scream as she narrowly avoided losing her grip on Thassalin's slippery scales.
"HOW CAN WE KILL HER? ", Nyssi screamed.
"AIM AT THEIR HEADS! "
"THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT! "
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, flying closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but it fell into slight panic when hit from behind by a stream of fire. It hadn't realized it wasn't alone. Its panic increased even more as Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail against its head, throwing it off course.
Snarling and hissing, she flew upwards and spat into the air. Suddenly everything turned dark as if the monster had sucked all the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly couldn't see anything anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before he finally crashed into an open clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot towards him, pulling the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!," Tenuk screamed as he glided out of the cloud and began to circle, searching for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Beneath them, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her unusual, supernatural healing powers were already taking effect. Unfortunately, the same didn't apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch-black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in this shadow, something screamed and screeched.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the ground and knocked her over. But she noticed that the tail was swinging wildly and not trying to hit her intentionally. The beast, or what Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, pierced the monster, and confused it.
Plötzlich krachte ein Gewehrschuss durch den Nebel, und das Monster verstummte, kollabierte auf dem Boden und blieb regungslos liegen. Die Dunkelheit um sie herum löste sich auf und sie sahen, was geschehen war: Auf der Bestie stand Kayel, der heftig keuchend sein Gewehr hielt.
"Das war wohl... Der verrückteste Schattensprung, den ich je gemacht habe... Thanto kat'olon...", rang Kabel nach Luft. Seine Augen glühten fast schwarz, und eine dunkle Energie umwirbelte seinen Körper. Aber während er noch sprach, kehrte die Farbe in seine Panzerung zurück, und seine Augen nahmen wieder ihre normale gelbe Farbe an."
Es dauerte einen Moment, bis Nyssi verstand, was geschehen war. Sie hatten alle gewusst, dass Kayel diese seltsamen Schattenkräfte besaß. Er nutzte sie selten, weil die meisten sie für unheimlich und ziemlich furchteinflößend hielten. Aber Nyssi hatte nicht gewusst, dass Kayel diese Kräfte auch in jeder Art von Dunkelheit einsetzen konnte. Und so wie Kayel sich benahm, war er offenbar auch ziemlich überrascht.
"Bist du ok?", brach es aus Nyssi heraus."
"Ja, mir geht es gut. Ich habe etwas getötet, ich werde gleich wieder in Ordnung sein." Kayel betrachtete sein Werk, während Tenuk herabflog, neben ihm landete und wieder seine normale Spast-Form annahm."
Now that the creature wasn't moving anymore, they could better see what it was. Its skin was raven-black and slimy, but the slime stayed firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell that thing was, something screeched and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't make it to them because a familiar vehicle plowed into its side, causing the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wasn't willing to take any risks. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
“Ups…” muttered Retvik from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and stepping out of the truck. “Ahm, that was actually not intentional. Are you all okay?”
“You missed all the action,” complained Tenuk. “Where were you?”
“You left me standing there. I came as fast as I could…,” sighed Retvik. “May I ask what those terrible creatures are?”
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had managed to pull himself together again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a little dazed, but not seriously injured.
“YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. THE ENTITIES THAT WERE FLEEING WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.”
“You mean the terrible god-monster entity that we… helped kill?” stammered Tenuk.
“YES. EXACTLY THAT. PERHAPS THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULD NOT SHOOT THE HEAD. I DID NOT HAVE A FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?” Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted his head. “THANK YOU VERY MUCH, SMALL ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES.”
“Uh… thank you… I guess…”, shrugged Kayel. “So, are we done here then?”
Nyssi shrugged. She picked up her camera and took a few photos of the now definitively dead creatures. Then she grabbed her favorite weapon, the decorated Death God dagger, and began cutting one of the creature's horns off. After that, she moved on to the next task. But just as Nyssi was finished, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ashes in seconds. The same happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
“So, this is both practical and impractical…,” Nyssi sighed. “But at least I have the photos, hopefully.”
